	<p>6. SOUNDBITE (English) Dr Neil Wilkin, curator of Early Europe, The British Museum:</p>
	<p>"In the exhibition, we explore the history of Stonehenge, we pull apart the different periods in which it was built and modified, and what we show is that there was no one Stonehenge. There were many different monuments that meant different things to different people at different times. And so you'll learn about how Stonehenge was at one time in its history a cemetery, for instance. And then later on, it became a place that's much more like a cathedral, somewhere where people went to worship and undertake ceremonies."</p>
